The most striking experience was the fusion between efficiency and security. 
While on the one hand, innovations like the Marine Smart Integrated System (MSIS) and low-code platforms support remarkable efficiency, 
where manual processes are used to eliminate congestion, on the other, the excellent security standards, with a 24/7 Security Operations Center (SOC) and Active-Active Data Centers, 
proved an unwavering commitment to safeguarding these critical infrastructure resources. It was aptly stated that innovation in this digital era must be founded on the principles of resilience.

Other than that, knowledge of their Business Continuity setup, comprising of disaster recovery centers and high-availability solutions framed IT as a core business enabler.
It clearly showed that system reliability is in direct relation to national trade and economic activity.

The sum of this visit was to connect the academic knowledge of systems, networking, and security to high-stakes application.
It showed that in our future role as technologists, we will design solutions which must be smart, efficient, yet fundamentally secure and reliable, considering their continuity in respect of providing essential services.
The visit showed how JohorPort combines modern technology,like low-code systems with strongsecurity and backup plans. Thisallows them to stay efficient and reliable.
